{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_knapweed_ver01/data/sn82006551/00393341981/1946021401/0057.xml":{"full_text":"Published every Thursday at Libby,\nMont., by Western Montana Pub\nlishing Company, Inc.\nEntered at the postoffice at Libby,\nMont., as second-class njatter.\nw LiTTELL I\nEditor and Manager\nI\n\n_ i__ n A\n4ATIONAL cPITOnlAL\ni\ni\nj\n\nI\nWestern News\nAND LIBBY TIMES\nn^lQSSQCIAriON\nI* I\n<m\nOFFICIAL PAPER FOR LINCOLN\nCOUNTY\n$2.501\n1 50\nThe proposed Kootenai dam story\nreprinted on another page, which\nappeared in last Saturday's Great\nFalls Tribune, has met with a diver-j\nsified reception among Libby and j\nTroy citizens. Many are skeptical j\nthat the proposition will ever get j\nbeyond the present stage; others\nbelieve it will probably receive!\nconsiderable promotion but like the j\nproposed raising of the water level j\non Flathead Lake some time back,\nbe defeated by popular disapproval 1\nSeveral have mentioned a qualified\napproval of the project. \u00ce\nShould the proposition ever re -1\nceive the approval of Congress\nwhich would be needed before it\nmight become a project, all pro -1\nper tv along the Kootenai Valley\nwhich would be subject to overflow\nfrom waters backed up by the dam\nwould have to be condemned and\nappraised by the government\nwhich would make settlement on\nthe basis of appraised value. All of\nwhich means that Troy, Libby and\nSubscription Kates:\nOne year\nSix months\nTHAT DAM STORY\nThe writer states that after bills\nfor materials, equipment and all\nother necessary running expenses\nincluding taxes etc., have been paid.\nj 92 cents out of each dollar went\nj to labor. These statistics are from\nja national business survey in 1944.\nHe goes on to state that of the re\nmaining 8 cents, over half is not\np ro fit but is put back into the busi\nness for future expansion. The\nstatement then follows that \"Only\nthree and one-half cents out of each\ndollar available in American indus\ntry and business last year (1944)\nwent to the owner of the business\nas a profit.\"\nMr. Drucker maintains there are\nonly two solutions to the problem,\nIndustry can charge higher prices\nfor products or else labor efficiency\nmust be raised. The first solution.\nhe claims defeats its own purpose\nby neutralizing labor's increased\nwages through their loss as\ncon- j\npaying higher prices. Thon\nfarmers and others whose in\nhave not been raised will be\nC|\ncomes\nunable to buy as much as before,\nthus the demand for the workers'\nproducts will go down, and with\nit. unemployment will result. j\nThe author's solution is increased\nproductivity per man hour. He uses\nthe raycn industry as an example. I\nBetween 1929 and 1941 the prod-\nuctivity of the rayon worker was j\nincreased four-fold by technology\ncal progress. During the same per-.\niod rayon prices were cut almost\ntwo-thirds, leading to a six-fold in- j\ncrease in consumption of the pro-\nduct. One of the best features of\nthis increase was that the wages of j\nthose employed in the industry i\nraised two-thirds and in spite of j i\ngreater h bor-hour production, 1\nmore men were employed at the i\npeak of the boom. During this\nperiod technological progress in- j\ncreased production in a similar, j\nthough in most cases marked scale j\nextensively throughout industry.\nWith the coming of the war. the j\npicture changed. Of twenty-one in 1\ndustries which the Depeartment, of\nLabor publishes details, eleven have I\ncontinued increased productivity\nthrough the war; in two industries.\nthe man-hour output remains the\nsame as in pre-war days, but in\nthe eight industries il\nby Charles D. Rowe\n\"Let them starve, what do I care,\nI'm not going to get along without\nall the white bread I want.\"\nOne might justly conclude that\nis the attitude of those who object\nto cooperating with President Tru\nman in his laudable endeavor to ac\ncumulate a supply of foo*ds here in\norder to avert \"mass starvation\"\nabroad. The President has ordered\ncertain restriction in food products\nwhich will require use of darker\nbread and far less whiskey and beer, j\nSaid the President: \"I know\nconscience of the American people i\nwill not permit them to withhold I\nShall We LetThem\nStarve Is Question\nWe Must Face\nor stint their cooperation while their\nfellowmen in other lands suffer and\ndie.\"\nFortunately the President is cor\nreel in that respect. Despite the\nfact that one congressman seemed\nto question the need for this food\ncurtailment, the great majoritv of\nthe A.mercan people will gladly\ncomply with the President's re\nouest. What sort of person would\ndo otherwise? We here in America\ns it down warm and comfortable to\nour tables and frequently eat more\nfrom our abundance than is good\nfor us. At the same time there are\nthousands\u2014yqs, even millions\u2014\ngoing hungry and cold in other\nlands. If there is a drop of the\n\"milk of human kindness\" in one's j\nmakeup, full and free cooperation j\ns the only thing possible. Guant,\nundernouriidhed children, innocent\nvictims of man's inhumanity, are\nreaching out to us to give them a!\nlittle from our abundance. Of coure,\nAmerica's response will be gener 1\nous.\n\nI had an interesting letter this\nweek from a Libby man. Cpl. Bill\nHafferman. who is with our armed\nforces in Manila, P. I. Hafferman\nwrites that he receives The West\nern News every week and reads:\n\"every- inch of it. thereby coming\nacross your interesting column. I\nit the of the and I\npapers quoting from Alcoholics An\nonymous, an organization of for\nmer drunks who are now striving\nto help cure others who have suc\ncumbed.\nAlcoholics Anonymous says there\nare 600.000 chronic female alcoholics\nin the United States. Interesting,\nisn't it? It also says there are two\nland a half million drunks in this\ncountry. And that there is one\nwoman drunk for every four alco-\nholies,\nThe president of Alcoholics Ano\nnymous says a great deal of drunk\nenness could be stopped if the av\nerage, normal drinking person real\nized that only one step separates\nhim or her from a chronic drunk,\n\"It's that first drink that counts.\nIt's that one drink that leads to\nthe!others, that leads to the chronic\nbinge,\" he says.\nJo 51 another little warning, girls,\n-Ctw\n\nm\n\n\u2022v\n'iff* {i/\nr\nwP\u00c9ki\nf\nDON'T WORRY!\nabout a way to spend these\nlong winter evenings. Just\ncome to.\nTHE PLAY\nBOWLING ALLEYS\nMr. and Mrs. F. C. Robertson and\nson, Thomas visited Saturday af\nternoon and Sunday with friends\nin Kalispell.\nLast Friday two of the Neils 'cats'\nmoved the Brinton house from its\nform\u00e2r\nLou\nlocation at the norh end\nsiana Ave., to its new loca\ntion southwest of he Courthouse.\nLibby's new hospital having from\n25 to 30 beds is to be located on\nthe former site of the Bpinton home.\nThe management hopes to get the\nhospital started this coming sum\nmer.\nof\nMr. and Mrs. William Perry of\nTroy, announce the birth last Sun\nday of a daughter. The young\nwoman who weighed 8 pounds had\nnot been n\u00e0med when her dad hand\ned us cigars last Tuesday.\nLibby friends were interested in\nthe announcment, received the first\nof the week, to the effect that an\n8 Vfe lb. son was born to the Rev.\nand Mrs. Russell Prentice at Kalis\npell on February 8 The Rev. Mr.\nPrentice was at one time pastor of\nthe First Presbytetian church in\nLibby.\nJUST ARRIVED!\n\nA COMPLETE NEW LINE\n\nof\n\u00df at It at a\n\n(foald\nCOSMETICS\nA\n\n\nKootenai Mercantile Co.\nDry Goods Dept.\nRex ford, as well as all villages and\nsettlements along tiw valley be\ntween these ponds would either be\ndestroyed or moved to new loca-,\ntions. In case of the latter even\ntuality. the government sometime^\nmoves an entire community.\nThe opinion of the majority of\ncitizens with whom we have\ntalked, is that the project would\nsimply bo another ruthless disre\ngar d of individual rights by the\ngovernment, and the destruction of\nthousands of acres of merchantable\ntimber and timberlands which the\ngovernment h'as been endeavoring\nto perpetuate forever by putting\nunder the Sustained Yield plan.\nThis destruction, they clhim, will\nmerely be to add waters to\nGrand Coulee project for further\nreclamation of \"marginal lands\"\nfor farming purposes. All who are\nacquainted with the farm situation!\ndur.ng the past decade, remember\nthe government curtailment of farm\ncrops in some of the nation's finest\nfarming country already under .cul\ntivation, and find it hard to recon\neile the destruction of so much\nproperty and fine timber lands in\nLincoln county, to provide more\nfarm land to compete with natural-1\nly good farm land so recently t-'e\nstricted from full production. An\nxamplc of governmental sagacity\nhas gone down. This does not in\n,elude new industries nor industries\nwhich retooled for production of,\nwar materials.\nDrucket then gives examples more\nor less familiar to the general pub-\nlie where in certain lines, wages\nhave gone up steeply and produc\nt;on has fallen. This he attributes\nnot to less efficient industry or la\nbor, but to change in products and\nmethods of production, the use of\ninexperienced labor, the strain un\nder which both industry and labor\nhave been working, and the wide-\nspread use of overtime.\nDrucker's hope for the future is\nrapid rise of industrial efii\n\ni the\nthejeiency and productivity and that\nj this rise may be sw'ift enough dur\nj ing the next year or two to catch\nj up wi th the jump in labor c osts.\nstaff OF 101\n1\nI Missoula, Mont., Montana's State\nun j ve rsity at Missoula will mark\nCharter dav and the first year\nLj j ts second half-century in a brief\nprogram Monday. Feb. 18. at which\nI q,. Harold C. Urey, noted atomic i\nt n \u00ea r gy scientist and graduate of the'\ni un ver sity in 1917. will discuss prob-\npms f ac j n tbe W orld with release\n0 f atomiC p OW cr.\nto\nwe really debated your January 101\ncolumn on servicemen.\"\n(Our January 10th column ex\npressed a sympathetic understand-,\ning of the soldier's desire to be re\nturned home, but questioned the\nwisdom r.f disbanding our armies\ntoo rapidly\u2014not until the job is\nfinished. \u00d6ur thought was that\nthousands of fine young men have\nbeen sacrificed to win the victory\nand destroy a monstrous evil in the\nworld. \"Now don't throw that vic\ntory away until it-is finished. The\nwaiting may be hard for the ser- j\nviccmen but let's see it through.)!\nHafferman goes on to say;\n\"We agree that Germany and\nJapan should be policed but why.\nthe Philippines? From what I have;\nseen and the transformation taken)\nplace in the past five months, they j\nare most capable of caring for!\nthemselves.\"\n\"We are re ally doing a good job j\n\u00b0I wasting an enormous amount of j\nmaterials and supplies as well as j\nmanpower.\" He writes bitterly a-|\nHout the waste and delay and adds:\n\"Why should they care? We will;\nHave to foot the bill.\"\n\"Don't worry too much about the'\nr0St \u00b0I I 10 world,\" he continues,\nur families are more important\nthan profits. We will protect them\nPeople are Talking\nAbout R. P. M. Motor Oil\nThe Oil that cleanses as it\nLubricates\nCleans out OLD Motors\nKeeps NEW Motors Clean\n30c a quart\n-CHANGE AT\nSERVICE\nSTATION\nOpen 9 a. m.\nto 9 p. m.\nTinker's\nON THE\nHIGHWAY\nJUST RECEIVED A SHIPMENT OF NEW TIRES\nin such matters, is in the minds of\nmany right now as they recall the\ngovernment's curtailment of swat\nbeet crops during the early 40 s,\nwhich has so drastically cut the\namount of sugar, coffee drinkers are\nable, to enjoy with their favorite\nbreakfast beverage.\nThe information published in\nthe Tribune article was released by\nFred-E. Buck, Chief Engineer of the\nState Water Conservation Board. A\nletter addressed to the publisher of\nThe Western News by Mr. Buck un\nder date of September 8 1945 in\nresponse to an inquiry on the army\nStudy being made below Troy.\ns tates in part:\nI believe at this time there is\nno need for the people of Troy to be\nexercised over the fact .that a dam\n.-ite is being diilleci in then ten i\ntory. CcT\u00fcinly no dam will ever be\nbuilt witnm the Basin until the\npeople in the neighborhood have\ni ad full information concerning\nth.-im tter. It is the policy of the\nArmy Engineers to hold a public\nhearing before attempting any ma\nOr development, and at such a\nhearing any objectors may have a\nvoice in inserting their objections\nm p the r r rd \"r .1 ..cr\nRegardless of the need, or lack of\nneed for excitement. South Lincoln\nCounty is pretty well stirred up re\nyarding the possibility of the pro\nposed reservoir. The columns of\nThe Western News will be open to\nall citizens of Lincoln County who\nmay wish to express their opinions\non this subject.\nSOURCE OF HIGHER WAGES\nOne of the most vital questions\nbefore the American public today\nis that of higher wages. Labor feels\nthe need of a higher wage to main\ntain living standards, and industry\ncontends that to pay this higher\nwage, it is necessary to receive a\nhigher-Tftettffie\u2014with which to Tncct\nthe rise in wages. It is a problem\nwhich has the best minds of the\ncountry more or less at sea. It is\na question that most of us feel is\ntoo deep for us to answer satisfac\ntorily.\nA recent article in The Saturday!of\nEvening Post, written by Petter F.\nDrucker offers one solution which,\nwhether feasible or not, will be of\ninterest to all our readers. A brief\nsummary of Mr. Drucker's ideas\nfollow:\nIn order to raise wages, income\nfur industry must also be raised.\nUnder James A. McCain, new\nrrPS irieni the university olims to\nS ^to people otMo\"\ntana by rcsea rch in* problems dir\nect y effecting their well-being and\nnm \u00ea n ei itv through extension and\ncorrespondence work\nThe third state legislature estab\nii s hed the university charter Feb\nj 7 18 93 Fifty students enrolled\nvvben t be school opened Sept. 10,\njggg a buiIding borrowed from\nMissoula school district\nPresent enrollment totals approxi\nmatcly 1.600 students, more than\none-third of whom are veterans, and\nan other 400 to 500 veterans are ex\npected next month when spring\nUar ter classes begin\nThe first campus buildings, open-1\n<>f j in j 899 werc provided by the\nS a j 0 a t a cost of $42.000 for Uni-1\nversity ha,l and $32.000 for Science\nb;i j] bo th in use today\n-p be university's present physical\nn i.. nf ao n nin and several minm\n^iuLis f aluvd a t's2.622.750\nThe original faculty of five head\nf f j j )y p r( .sident Oscar J. Craig has\n\u201ennvn to a staff t f 101 full-time\nmembers and 15 i art-time instru\nin 2 o dei rtments nf iho\nCollege of Arts and Sciences and\nthe professional schools of business\nadministration, education, forestry.\nj ourn alism. law. music and phar\nniacy.\n\"Montana oconle have a better\nUniversity than they realize\" Me\nCain said\nThrough these resources provided\nby the pepole of Montana, \"the Uni\nversity aims to assist the people of\nthe stae in every walk of life no\nmatter what their business or pro\nfession.\"\nthe American Red Cross,\nLibby.\nW, T. Smith of this city, claims\nto be one of the first pair of twins\nborn in Libby. His twin brother,\nJohn only lived nine weeks.\nMrs. Bert Wallbridge, who has\nbeen in a tiospitnl recovering from\na gall bladder operation, was able\nto return home last -Sunday.\nV. A. Dtmkle and J. K. Farris\nof Troy, members of the executive\ncommittee of the Troy branch of\nthe South Lincoln County Chapter\nwere\nin Libby Monday night to meet\nwith Libby officials of the Red\nCross. Plans were discussed for\nthe forthcoming Red Cross Fund\nDrive, to be staged from March 1\nto 31. Mrs. Hal Hepner will be\nchairman in charge of the drive in\nw ien CHe n00C I arises but why poke\ni our nose into other people's busi\n\"\u00abs?\n1 \"I really enjoy your column and\nbuddies also enjoy it. Keep\n1 U P I 10 good work. But remember,\n1 they aren't interested in Washing\nj ton D c over economy and we\nsoldiers are.\"\n\nJudging from this distance and\nwhat one can read in the news\npapers, it would be a wise thing\n'f Edwin W. Pauley would grace\nfully retire as a candidate for ap\nP\u00b0 intment as undersecretary of the\nnavy- President Truman has nomi\nnatcd Him for lhat position.\nsome quite considerable fireworks\nhavc resulted. Pauley's appoint\nnu nt must be confirmed by the\nsena I 0\nIn Hearing before the senate\nnaval committee. Secretary of the\nInterior Ickes' produced a memor\nandum dated Sept. 6 1944. which\nsa d Pauley had put up to him\n(Ickes) \"the rawest proposition that\nHas ever been made to me.\" Ickcs\ntestified Pauley told him oilmen\nwould chip in $300,000 in political\ncontributions if they were assured\nthe government would not file suit\n1 to obtain title to oil lands off the\ncoasts Pauley was democratic na\ntional treasurer at the time. He is\na so a California oil man. There\nis a contest on between the govern\nment Snd private interests as to\nwho is entitled to oM that may be\nI\u00b0 und in tidelands extending from\nthe shore out to the three mile\n\u00fc m >t\nAnd\nPauley denies vehemently that he\never made such a statement to Ick\nes. But Ickes charges have been\nsubstantiated by the testimony of\nanother witness. President Truman\nstands back of Pauley and insists\nthat he is an honest man.\nPauley may be an honest man\nand naturally would like confirma^\ntion now in view of the charges\nhe faces. But whether he is hon\nest or not, there will be a suspicion\nin the minds of the public* It j\nwould be constantly asked, \"Would I\nj Ickes dare to make such a charge\nif it were not true.\" Better keep I\nclear of such an cntangletnent. We\ndo not want another Teapot Dome\nsmelly mess.\n\n\"That trembling hand that clut\nches the cocktails in the nation's\nbars these days isn't a man's\u2014it's\na woman's.\"\nSo says a news item in Monday's\nNEXT STOP-IGA\n\nM\ni My wife intieta 